solutions.content:
A classic problem that I wanted to tackle with a fancier approach than usual, so I went for a bitwise approach, which would have been ideal with a more contained set of characters and ended up being a bit more painful than necessary having to support more than `64` (ie: 8 bytes worth) characters.

To proceed, we will declare a few variables:
* `res` will store our ongoing result, with the longest sequence found so far, initially set to `0`;
* `tmp` will store thee length of the currently parsed longest subsequence withut repetitions, preset to `0` as well;
* `mask1` and `mask2` are our bitmasks to keep track of the already seen characters - again assigned an initial value of `0`;
* `bit` and `base` will help us work on the bitmasks, updating them, with `base` being initialised to `1` and never changing its value from there.

Notice that I declared all of them as `long long`, including `base` (to avoid having to convert `1` all the time), so that all in all we can use `64 + 64 == 128` bits worth of mask, more than enough for our current needs.

We will then iterate through `i` up to the end of the string, using also the temporary variable `c`. We will:
* to store the value of the current character in `c`;
* compute `bit` left-shifting `base` by a value always in the `0 - 63` range;
* check with our bitmasks if we already found that character and, in case, since it means we just finished a viable subsequence:
	* update `res` as the maximum between its current value and `tmp`;
	* reset `tmp`, `mask1` and `mask2` all to `0`;
	* backtrack. and reset `i` to be on the first previous occurrence of `c`;
* if instead it is the first time we are encountering it, we will:
	* increase `tmp` by `1`;
	* update either `mask1` or `mask2` with `bit`.

Once we are done, we will again compute the maximum between `res` and `tmp`, so to capture also sequences that included the very last character, and return it :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLongestSubstring(string s) {
        int res = 0, tmp = 0;
        long long mask1 = 0, mask2 = 0, bit, base = 1 ;
        for (int i = 0, lmt = s.size(), c; i < lmt; i++) {
            // updating c and bit
            c = s[i];
            bit = base << (c < 64 ? c : c - 64);
            // character already used
            if ((c < 64 ? mask1 : mask2) & bit) {
                res = max(res, tmp);
                tmp = mask1 = mask2 = 0;
                // backtracking i
                while (s[--i] != c);
            }
            // character not used before
            else {
                tmp++;
                (c < 64 ? mask1 : mask2) |= bit;
            }
        }
        return max(res, tmp);
    }
};
```

Now, you might notice that with that backtracking logic we are going to potentially recompute a lot of the already parsed string and it is here that a 2 pointers approach shines.

Most of the code is the same, but we will never completely reset `mask1` and `mask2`, instead we will just use 2 pointers `i` and `j` to delimit our substring, normally advancing with `j` until we find an already seen character, in which case we advance `i` right after the previous occurrence of the same character, erasing the matching bits in our bitmasks, but without redoing the same work twice: it is about 7-8 time faster, with basically the same memory consumption:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLongestSubstring(string s) {
        int res = 0, tmp = 0;
        long long mask1 = 0, mask2 = 0, bit, base = 1 ;
        for (int i = 0, j = 0, lmt = s.size(), c; j < lmt; j++) {
            // updating c and bit
            c = s[j];
            bit = base << (c < 64 ? c : c - 64);
            // character already used
            if ((c < 64 ? mask1 : mask2) & bit) {
                res = max(res, tmp);
                // advancing i
                while (s[i] != c) {
                    (c < 64 ? mask1 : mask2) ^= base << (s[i] < 64 ? s[i] : s[i] - 64);
                    i++;
                };
                i++;
                tmp = j - i + 1;
            }
            // character not used before
            else {
                tmp++;
                (c < 64 ? mask1 : mask2) |= bit;
            }
        }
        return max(res, tmp);
    }
};
```

