So, for that one, I have a very simplest way for you to solve this problem. If you look at the example
```
[2,6,4,8,10,9,15]
   ^        ^
 start     end
```
From our start point everything on the right is smaller,so that means the starting point value will be greater & similarly if you look at our end point everything on the left to it is greater & end point is smaller. So, if somehow we sort them then our array become sorted. Because as you see the start pointer has to exist on the right side not over there & similarly the end pointer has to exist on left side not over there.

Thus, if we get our end index & start index so, we will gonna calculate the window size by this formula :- **`end - start + 1`**

**So, ya let's look at the code**
```
class Solution {
    public int findUnsortedSubarray(int[] nums) {
        int end = -1;
        int max = nums[0];
        for(int i = 1; i < nums.length; i++){
            if(max > nums[i]){ // the left value is greater then current value
                end = i; // mark that index with end
            }
            else{
                max = nums[i];
            }
        }

        int start = 0;
        int min = nums[nums.length - 1];
        for(int i = nums.length - 2; i >= 0; i--){
            if(min < nums[i]){ // the right value is smaller then current value
                start = i; // mark that index with start
            }
            else{
                min = nums[i];
            }
        }
        return end - start + 1;
    }
}
```

ANALYSIS :-
* **Time Complexity :-** O(N) + O(N) = 2O(N) => BigO(N)

* **Space Complexity :-** BigO(1)

