solutions.content:
Solving it sorting a copy of the vector and comparing it to the input is trivial; and rather expensive.

We can do better.

And to do better, we first of all need to find the first and the final segment of the vector which are sorted (either of them might be empty - ie: 0 sorted elements) and then work on the central part which is not.

We start declaring a few variables:
* `i` and `j` are our pointers, respectively pointing to the first (`0`) and last (`nums.size() - 1`) element of the input;
* `vMin` and `vMax` will be used later, to find the lowest and highest value in the unsorted central part.

We will then move `i` left and `j` right until they point to sorted elements and do not cross each other, so that we will know that the `[0, i]` and `[j, nums.size() - 1]` segments are sorted, while `[i + 1, j - 1]` is not.

Now, if `i == j` our life is easier: the vector is fully sorted and we can just return `0` directly.

If not, we need to figure out `vMin` and `vMax` as the lowest and highest value respectively in `[i + 1, j - 1]`, setting them to the values immediately before it.

Note: we can be sure that at least one of them will be different from the initial value, since otherwise we would be dealing with an already sorted vector if `nums[i] <= vMin <= vMax <= nums[j]`.

Once we found the value(s) of the central part that need(s) to be relocated, we might be tempted to just go and linearly check where in the first or last segment `vMin` or `vMax` might respectively go.

And that would work, but since we know that `[0, i]` and `[j, nums.size() - 1]` are indeed sorted, we have a more powerful way to get things done: binary search will find us where to insert them in logarithmic time!

Since I felt lazy by this point, I just used `upper_bound` and `lower_bound` respectively to know where to place `vMin` and `vMax` and thus update the values of `i` and `j` if needed, but be ready to write your own function in an interview.

Once done, we can just return `j - i` to know how many elements are in the range that needs to be sorted :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        // support variables
        int i = 0, j = nums.size() - 1, vMin, vMax;
        // moving i to the first unsorted element
        while (i < j && nums[i] <= nums[i + 1]) i++;
        // moving i to the first unsorted element
        while (i < j && nums[j] >= nums[j - 1]) j--;
        // edge case: all sorted
        if (j == i) return 0;
        // finding vMin and vMax
        vMin = nums[i], vMax = nums[j];
        for (int k = i; k <= j; k++) {
            vMin = min(nums[k], vMin);
            vMax = max(nums[k], vMax);
        }
        // moving i and j to the newer positions, if needed
        if (vMin < nums[i]) i = upper_bound(begin(nums), begin(nums) + i, vMin) - begin(nums);
        if (vMax > nums[j]) j = lower_bound(begin(nums) + j, end(nums), vMax) - begin(nums);
        return j - i;
    }
};
```

