solutions.content:
In the first pass, we move forward and keep track of the current maximum. If we see an element that is less than the current maximum, then the minimal unsorted subarray must contain this element. We record the last such element.

In the second pass, we move backward and keep track of the current minimum. If we see an element that is greater than the current minimum, then the minimal unsorted subarray must contain this element. We record the first such element.

The answer is just the range between the two recorded elements.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int end = 0;
        int maximum = nums[0];
        for (int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if (nums[i] < maximum) {
                end = i + 1;
            }
            else {
                maximum = nums[i];
            }
        }

        int start = nums.size();
        int minimum = nums[nums.size() - 1];
        for (int i = nums.size() - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (nums[i] > minimum) {
                start = i;
            }
            else {
                minimum = nums[i];
            }
        }

        return max(end - start, 0);
    }
};
```

