There are five major cases need to be considered
1. Unsorted array at the start. Ex : [2,3,1,  4,5]
2. Unsorted array at the last. Ex : [1,2,3,  5,4]
3. Unsorted array in the middle. Ex : [1,2,3,   5,6,4  ,7,8]
4. Total array is unsorted Ex: [5,4,8,9,1]
5. Complete array is already sorted [1,2,3,4,5]



Lets take [1,2,4,2,8,9,2] as input

Approach:
1. We will declare an extra array (lets say arr) of length as same of input
2. Traverse the array from right to left, and update the last maximum element in the extra array in the respective index (Like Prefix sum array)
3. Now traverse the array from left to right, and **compare the last maximum and current element are same if not update the start and end of the unsorted array** and update the last minimum element in the extra array in the respective index (Like Prefix sum array)


A detailed view on the above approach with separate arrays for each traversals.

Input : 
[1,2,4,2,8,9,2]

After right to left traversal,
[1,2,2,2,2,2,2]

After second traversal (left to right)
[1,2,4,4,8,9,9]

Comparing the above two
[1,2,  2,2,2,2,2]
[1,2,  4,4,8,9,9]

We can say the change starts from 3rd position and continues upto the end


C++ code:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int size = nums.size();
        int arr[size], i, start = -1, end = -1;

        // Right to Left Traverse
        for(i = size-2, arr[size-1] = nums[size-1]; i >= 0; i--)
            arr[i] = min(nums[i], arr[i+1]);

        int flag = arr[0] == nums[0];
        start = flag ? -1 : 0;
        arr[0] = nums[0];

        // Left to Right Traverse
        for(i= 1, arr[0] = nums[0];i < size ;i++){

            int temp = max(nums[i], arr[i-1]);

            // Current element is not the last maximum element
            if(temp != arr[i]){
                if(flag) // Unsorted array starts here from this index
                    start = i, flag = 0;
                else // Continuously updating the end value as current index until sorted array starts
                    end = i;
            }

            // Updating the last maximum element
            arr[i] = temp;
        }

        return (start == -1) ? 0 : end-start+1;
    }
};
```

