# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I found several good solutions here. But no one is really **one-pass**. Some of them just combine two loops into one. But each element is visited twice but not once. This solution provides a **one-pass** solution. 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The main idea is the same. Let the solution be [$left$, $right$].  Then, $left$ is the first index with a smaller element on its right side, and $right$ is last index with a larger element on it left side. We can find $right$ by sweeping from left to right and keeping the prefix minimum. Similar for finding $left$. But it takes two passes, either in two loops or one loops.

The improvement here is as follows.
First, go forward from head to find the longest nondecreasing sequence $nums[0]$ ~ $nums[i]$. Similarly, go backward from tail to find the longest nondecreasing sequence $nums[j]$ ~ $nums[n-1]$. 
Then we find the maximum ($pmax$) and minimum ($pmin$) in the range $[i, j]$. So far, each element is visited exactly once. Finally, $left$ can be found by performing binary seach $pmin$ in the nondecreasing sequence $nums[0]$ ~ $nums[i]$. Similar for finding $right$.    


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n)$, each element visited once, plus two binary searches.  
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $O(1)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    // Let the solution be [left,right].
    // Then, left is the first index with a smaller element on its right side.
    // right is last index with a larger element on it left side.
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n=nums.size(),i,j,k,pmax,pmin;
        if (n == 1) return 0;
        // find non-decreasing sequence at head
        for (i=0; i<n-1 && nums[i]<=nums[i+1]; ++i);
        if (i == n-1) return 0; // sorted case
        // find nondecreasing sequence at tail
        for (j=n-1; nums[j]>=nums[j-1]; --j);
        /* this is one-pass but a little bit slower than using min_element
        pmax = pmin = nums[i];
        for (k=i+1; k<=j; ++k) {
            if (nums[k] > pmax) pmax=nums[k];
            else if (nums[k] < pmin) pmin = nums[k];
        }*/
        pmax = *max_element(nums.begin()+i, nums.begin()+j+1);
        pmin = *min_element(nums.begin()+i, nums.begin()+j+1);
        // binary search to find left and right
        return lower_bound(nums.begin()+j, nums.end(),pmax) - \
        upper_bound(nums.begin(),nums.begin()+i, pmin);
    }
};
```

