Taken a vector to store the given array(nums) in ascending order. Taken two variables s and e. s for holding the position  of first element in the nums whose position didn't match in the sorted array similary e is holding the position of last element in the array whose position didn't match in the sorted array.

example: 
 nums[] = [2,1,0,4,5]
 v[] = [0,1,2,4,5]
 s will be 0 because 0th element in the nums is not equal to 0th element of v similary e will be 2 because 2nd element of nums is not equal to 2nd element of v.
hence length of smallest unsorted array will be  s-e+1  (because given array have 0 indexing)

special cases:
If these is only one element in the array or if the array is already sorted then the value of s and e remain 0 so you can directly return 0.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int s=0,e=0;    
      vector<int>v(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());

        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(v[i]!=nums[i]){
                s=i;
                break;
            }
        }

        for(int i=nums.size()-1;i>s;--i){
            if(v[i]!=nums[i]){
                e=i;
                break;
            }
        }
        if(s==0 && e==0){
            return 0;
        }
        return e-s+1;
    }

};
```

