solutions.content:
The idea is fairly simple. 

If we consider a left subarray till 'i', then nums[i] should be maximum in that subarray. And if it's not the max element met so for, then definitely it's unsorted and can be the potential end point of desired subarray.

We can think similarly for right subarray. To avoid one more iteration, we have taken j = nums.size()-1-i. So, nums[j] should me mimimum in the right subarray. And if it's not, then definitely it's unsorted and can be the potential start point of desired subarray.

'start' and 'end' won't be updated in case of an already sorted array.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int findUnsortedSubarray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int leftmax = INT_MIN, rightmin = INT_MAX;
        int start = -1, end = -1, ans;

        for(int i = 0; i<nums.size(); i++){
            int j = nums.size()-1-i;

            leftmax = max(leftmax, nums[i]);
            rightmin = min(rightmin, nums[j]);

            if(leftmax!=nums[i]) end = i;
            if(rightmin!=nums[j]) start = j;
        }

        ans = (end==start)? 0 : (end-start+1);
        return ans;
    }
};

