Went through the forum but couldnt find anything similar. If you are having difficulties understanding the solution section or the solutions posted, this might help.

**Intuition and approach** :
In the best case scenario the shortest subarray (i,j) will be the one that is bounded  by two pairs of sorted arrays. one from 0 to i and one from j to len-1. But the subarray (i,j) can have numbers that are :
* Smaller than the numbers in the left subarray
* Bigger than the numbers in the right subarray 

If thats the case then we need to include them as well. So we increase the boundaries by moving i towards the left and j towards the right.

**Code**
```
class Solution {
    public int findUnsortedSubarray(int[] nums) {
        int i = 0, j = nums.length-1;

        while(i < nums.length-1 && nums[i] <= nums[i+1]) i++; // finding sorted position.
        if (i == nums.length-1) return 0; // fully sorted
        while(j > 0 && nums[j] >= nums[j-1]) j--; //finding sorted pos from end of array

        //increasing boundaries while going through our best case subarray
        for (int m = i; m <= j; m++) {
            while(i>0 && nums[m] < nums[i-1]) i--; // remember that 0 to i-1 is already sorted.
            while(j<nums.length-1 && nums[m] > nums[j+1]) j++; // similarly j to length-1 is also sorted.
        }

        return j-i+1; 
    }
}
```

Suggestions are always welcome. 
And do let me know if you see any discrepancy in my solution.

